body_html:
@andrewharp I am sorry, if I was too unclear.
I am using a Nexus 6P as host device.
Input size (12593) and model architecture are given by #issuecomment-289561458
I will now measure the times myself and post the results.

Sorry for the confusion: I am referring to the (recently renamed) methods of TensorFlowInferenceInterface. Previously, feed was the only one to be listed at all. After some changes to the computation graph, run is now said to account for about a fifth of the time that feed takes and fetch wasn't listed so far.

Yes, I know that they are independent from one another but they are usually called together.
I am looking forward to my manual measuring results.

Yes, I am still using the Android Monitor over ADB to perform Method Tracing.

body:
@andrewharp I am sorry, if I was too unclear.
I am using a **Nexus 6P** as host device.
Input size (**12593**) and model architecture are given by #issuecomment-289561458
I will now measure the times myself and post the results.

Sorry for the confusion: I am referring to the (recently renamed) methods of [`TensorFlowInferenceInterface`](https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/blob/master/tensorflow/contrib/android/java/org/tensorflow/contrib/android/TensorFlowInferenceInterface.java). Previously, `feed` was the only one to be listed at all. After some changes to the computation graph, `run` is now said to account for about a fifth of the time that `feed` takes and `fetch` wasn't listed so far.

Yes, I know that they are independent from one another but they are usually called together.
I am looking forward to my manual measuring results.

Yes, I am still using the Android Monitor over ADB to perform Method Tracing.
